### Grassmann Manifold Defined as Quotient Manifold

Definition of a Grassmann ManifoldA Grassmann manifold \(\operatorname{Gr}(k,D)\) is a set of \(k\)-dimensional subspaces \(\operatorname{span}(\bm{Y})\) (\(\bm{Y}\) is a matrix of \(k\) basis vectors and the function \(\operatorname{span}(\cdot)\) is onto \(\operatorname{Gr}(k,D)\)) in the \(D\)-dimensional Euclidean space \(\mathbb{R}^{D}\), and is defined as \(\operatorname{Gr}(k,D)=\left\{\operatorname{span}(\bm{Y})\subset\mathbb{R}^{D }\mid\dim\left(\operatorname{span}(\bm{Y})\right)=k\right\}\) (Absil et al. (2008)). The \(\operatorname{span}(\bm{Y})\) is the same subspace regardless of a \(k\)-dimensional rotation or \(k\)-dimensional reflection applied to \(\bm{Y}\) on which it is spanned. With respect to the compact Stiefel manifold \(\operatorname{St}(k,D):=\left\{\bm{Y}\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times k}\mid\bm{Y}^{ \top}\bm{Y}=\bm{I}_{k}\right\}\) defined as the set of \(D\times k\)-orthonormal basis matrices \(\bm{Y}\), the equivalence class of \(\bm{Y}\in\operatorname{St}(k,D)\) determined from the equivalence relation \(\sim\)2 is defined by \(\left[\bm{Y}\right]:=\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)=\left\{\bm{Y}\bm{Q}\in\operatorname {St}(k,D)\mid\bm{Q}\in\mathcal{O}(k)\right\}\), where \(\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)\) is a continuous surjection referred to as a quotient map. The equivalence class corresponds one-to-one with the \(k\)-dimensional subspace:

Footnote 2: When there exists some \(\bm{Q}\in\mathcal{O}(k)\) such that \(\bm{X}=\bm{Y}\bm{Q}\), then \(\bm{X}\) and \(\bm{Y}\) are defined to be equivalences \(\bm{X}\sim\bm{Y}\). Appendix D.2 provides further details.

\[\left[\bm{Y}\right]=\left[\bm{X}\right]\Longleftrightarrow\operatorname{span }(\bm{Y})=\operatorname{span}(\bm{X})\,,\] (1)

where \(\bm{Y}\in\operatorname{St}(k,D)\) is the representative of \(\left[\bm{Y}\right]\). \(\operatorname{span}(\bm{Y})\) is termed invariant under \(\sim\). The quotient set composed of such \(\left[\bm{Y}\right]\) as a whole can introduce the structure of a manifold (Sato & Iwai (2014)).

**Definition 1**.: _A Grassmann manifold as a quotient manifold is defined as follows:_

\[\operatorname{Gr}(k,D):=\operatorname{St}(k,D)\left/\mathcal{O}(k)=\left\{[ \bm{Y}]=\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)\mid\bm{Y}\in\operatorname{St}(k,D)\right\},\] (2)

