### ODE Solver with Orthogonal Integration

We present an ordinary differential equation (ODE) solver on \(\operatorname{Gr}(k,D)\). Celledoni & Owren (2002) proposed an intrinsic ODE solver that was applicable to \(\operatorname{St}(k,D)\) and did not assume an outer Euclidean space. This solver works on \(\operatorname{St}(k,D)\), thus it must be reformulated into a solver suitable for \(\operatorname{Gr}(k,D)\). We introduce a solver on \(\operatorname{Gr}(k,D)\) via ODE operating on \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\operatorname{St}(k,D)\), based on results from Section 4. This is an intrinsic approach regardless of whether the manifold has been embedded in a bigger space with a corresponding extension of the vector field. The ODE defined on \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\operatorname{St}(k,D)\) is obtained as:

\[\frac{d\mathsf{Vec}\left(\epsilon\left(t\right)\right)}{dt}=\nabla_{\gamma} \overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}^{-1}\mathsf{Vec}\left(\mathsf{X}_{\theta}\left(t, \gamma\left(t\right)\right)\right)\text{ s.t. }\gamma\left(t\right)=\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\left( \epsilon\left(t\right)\right),\] (8)

where \(\epsilon:[0,\infty)\to T_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\operatorname{St}(k,D)\) is the curve on \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\operatorname{St}(k,D)\), \(\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\) denotes the horizontal retraction, \(\nabla_{\gamma}\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}^{-1}\) can be calculated using (55) and \(\mathsf{Vec}\) denotes the map of vertically concatenating matrices and converting them into a single vector. Further details on our ODE can be found in Appendix C.1.

### Loss Function

The total change in log-likelihood using GrCNF can be calculated using the following equation.

\[\log p_{\theta}\left(\bm{Y}\left(t_{1}\right)\right)=\log p_{\operatorname{ Gr}(k,D)}\left(F_{\mathsf{X},t_{1}\theta}^{-1}\left(\bm{Y}\left(t_{1} \right)\right)\right)-\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\operatorname{div}\left(\mathsf{X}_ {\theta}\left(t,\bm{Y}\left(t\right)\right)\right)dt,\] (9)

where \(F_{\mathsf{X},t_{1}\theta}\) is a flow. In this study, we defined the loss function \(\operatorname{Loss}\) for maximizing the log-likelihood: \(\operatorname{Loss}=\operatorname{NLL}=-\log p_{\theta}\left(\bm{Y}\left(t_{1} \right)\right)\) where \(\operatorname{NLL}\) denotes negative log-likelihood.

