\[\bm{I}_{k}=\bm{Y}_{1}^{\top}\bm{Y}_{1}=\bm{Q}^{\top}\bm{Y}_{2}^{\top}\bm{Y}_{2 }\bm{Q}=\bm{Q}^{\top}\bm{Q}.\] (71)

Thus, there exists a \(k\)-dimensional orthogonal matrix \(\bm{Q}\in\mathcal{O}(k)\). As the subspace \(\mathrm{span}(\bm{Y})\) is invariant to coordinate transformations by orthogonal matrices, \(\mathrm{span}(\bm{Y}_{1})=\mathrm{span}(\bm{Y}_{2})\) is true.

