The equivalence class of \(\bm{Y}\in\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) is denoted by \([\bm{Y}]\). In other words, \([\bm{Y}]\) is the set of all elements of \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) that are equivalent to \(\bm{Y}\), and the equivalence relation on \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) divides \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) into equivalence classes with no intersection. Thus, \(\bm{Y}\) is then referred to as the representative of the equivalence class \([\bm{Y}]\). The set of equivalence classes is denoted \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)/\!\sim\) and is referred to as the quotient of \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) by the equivalence relation \(\sim\). In addition, \(\pi:\rightarrow\mathrm{St}(k,D)\rightarrow\mathrm{St}(k,D)/{\sim}\) is the natural projection that maps \(\bm{Y}\in\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) onto its equivalence class \([\bm{Y}]\). This projection \(\pi\) is surjection.

### Quotient Manifold

**Definition 3**.: _Let \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) be a manifold with equivalence relation \(\sim\). The quotient space \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}/{\sim}\) with \(\sim\) of \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) is the set of all equivalence classes. Thus, \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}/{\sim}:=\left\{\pi\left(\overline{\bm{x}}\right)\mid \overline{\bm{x}}\in\overline{\mathcal{M}}\right\}\), where \(\pi:\overline{\mathcal{M}}\rightarrow\overline{\mathcal{M}}/{\sim}\) is the natural projection and \(\pi\left(\overline{\bm{x}}\right):=\left\{\overline{\bm{y}}\in\overline{ \mathcal{M}}\mid\overline{\bm{y}}\sim\overline{\bm{x}}\right\}\). Then, \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) is referred to as the total space or the total manifold. Moreover, \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}/{\sim}\) is referred to as a quotient manifold of \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) if \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}/{\sim}\) admits a differentiable structure._

Let \(\mathcal{M}=\overline{\mathcal{M}}/{\sim}\) be a quotient manifold. Further, suppose that \(\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) is endowed with a Riemann metric \(\overline{g}\), and let \(\bm{x}=\pi\left(\bm{x}\right)\). The horizontal space \(T_{\overline{\bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{h}}\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) is the orthogonal complement of the vertical space \(T_{\overline{\bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{v}}\overline{\mathcal{M}}:=T_{\overline{\bm{x} }}\pi^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)\) in the tangent space \(T_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) and is defined as the follows:

\[T_{\overline{\bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{h}}\overline{\mathcal{M}}:=\left(T_{\overline{ \bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{v}}\overline{\mathcal{M}}\right)^{\perp}=\left\{\overline{ \bm{\eta}}_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\in T_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\overline{\mathcal{M}} \mid\overline{g}_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\left(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\overline{\bm{x }}},\overline{\bm{\eta}}_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\right)=0,\right.^{\forall} \overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\in T_{\overline{\bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{v}} \overline{\mathcal{M}}\right\}.\] (72)

The horizontal lift \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\overline{\bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{h}}\in T_{\overline{\bm{x}}} ^{\mathrm{h}}\overline{\mathcal{M}}\) of the tangent vector \(\bm{\xi}_{\bm{x}}\in T_{\bm{x}}\mathcal{M}\) at point \(\overline{\bm{x}}\in\pi^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)\) is a tangent vector that is uniquely determined as \(d\pi_{\overline{\bm{x}}}\left(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\overline{\bm{x}}}^{\mathrm{ h}}\right)=\bm{\xi}_{\bm{x}}\) (Absil et al. (2008)).

