\[T_{\bm{I}_{k}}\mathcal{O}(k) =T_{\bm{I}_{k}}\mathrm{St}(k,k)\] (90) \[=\left\{\bm{I}_{k}\bm{C}+\left(\bm{I}_{k\perp}\bm{B}=\bm{0}_{k} \right)\ \middle|\ \bm{C}\in\mathrm{Skew}\left(k\right),\bm{B}\in\mathbb{R}^{(k-k=0)\times k}\right\}\] (91) \[=\mathrm{Skew}\left(k\right).\] (92)Thus, we obtain the following formula.

\[T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)=\left\{\bm{Y}\bm{C}\mid\bm{C}\in{\rm Skew}\left( k\right)\right\}.\] (93)

Next, we define the horizontal space \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) as the orthogonal complement of \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) in \(T_{\bm{Y}}{\rm St}(k,D)\) endowed with the inner product (87).

\[T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D): =\left(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\right)^{\perp}\] (94) \[=\left\{\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\in T_{\bm{Y}}{\rm St }(k,D)\;\Big{|}\;{\rm tr}\left(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h\top}\overline {\bm{\eta}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\right)=0,\overline{\bm{\eta}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\in T _{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\right\}.\] (95)

Based on the fact that \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) is a subspace of \(T_{\bm{Y}}{\rm St}(k,D)\) and \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) is defined as its orthogonal complement, the direct sum decomposition is as follows.

\[T_{\bm{Y}}{\rm St}(k,D)=T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\oplus T_{\bm{Y}}^{ \rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\,,\] (96)

where \(\oplus\) denotes direct sum. Moreover, the tangent space is a linear space (Absil et al. (2008)). From (86), element \(\bm{Y}\bm{C}\) of \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm v}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) corresponds to the first term of (93); thus, (96) is formulated as follows:

\[T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)=\left\{\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h} =\bm{Y}_{\perp}\bm{B}\;\Big{|}\;\bm{B}\in\mathbb{R}^{(D-k)\times k}\right\}.\] (97)

Note that the horizontal vector \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\) is not necessarily an orthogonal matrix.

Finally, define the element \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\in T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) of the horizontal space at \(\bm{Y}\in{\rm St}(k,D)\) for the tangent vector \(\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\in T_{[\bm{Y}]}\;{\rm Gr}(k,D)\) at \([\bm{Y}]\in{\rm Gr}(k,D)\) as satisfying the following formula.

\[d\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)\left[\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\right]=\bm{ \xi}_{[\bm{Y}]},\] (98)

where \(d\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right):T_{\bm{Y}}{\rm St}(k,D)\to T_{[\bm{Y}]}\;{\rm Gr}(k,D)\) is the derivative \(\frac{d\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)}{d\bm{Y}}\) of \(\pi:{\rm St}(k,D)\to{\rm Gr}(k,D)\) at \(\bm{Y}\in{\rm St}(k,D)\). The \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\in T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) is referred to as the horizontal lift at \(\bm{Y}\in{\rm St}(k,D)\) of \([\bm{Y}]\in{\rm Gr}(k,D)\).

We describe the tangent space of \({\rm Gr}(k,D)\) with the concept of horizontal lift.

**Definition 5**.: _Let \(T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) be a horizontal space on \({\rm St}(k,D)\). Then, we define the tangent space \(T_{[\bm{Y}]}\;{\rm Gr}(k,D)\) of the \({\rm Gr}(k,D)\) as follows._

\[T_{[\bm{Y}]}\;{\rm Gr}(k,D)=\left\{\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\;\Big{|}\;d\pi\left(\bm {Y}\right)\left[\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\right]=\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}] },\;\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\in T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D) \right\}.\] (99)

From the above, \(\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\in T_{[\bm{Y}]}\;{\rm Gr}(k,D)\) is obtained from the map \(d\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)\left[\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\right]\) when \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\) is obtained. The \(\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\) is defined by an equivalence class and cannot be treated numerically in matrix form; however, it is sufficient to obtain the \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\) for actual numerical calculations. For \(\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\in T_{[\bm{Y}]}\;{\rm Gr}(k,D)\), there exists a \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\in T_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\;{\rm St}(k,D)\) that uniquely satisfies (98). In other words, we can handle it in matrix form by using elements of the horizontal space of Stiefel manifolds through the concept of horizontal lifting. Figure 1 is a conceptual diagram of the tangent space representation of a Grassmann manifold by horizontal lift.

#### d.4.4 Riemannian Metric on a Grassmann Manifold

We define the Riemannian metric \(g\) of \({\rm Gr}(k,D)\) through the concept of horizontal lift.

**Definition 6**.: _Let \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\) and \(\overline{\bm{\eta}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\) be the horizontal lifts that become \(d\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)\left[\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\right]=\bm{ \xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\) and \(d\pi\left(\bm{Y}\right)\left[\overline{\bm{\eta}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}\right]=\bm{ \eta}_{[\bm{Y}]}\), respectively. Then, we define the Riemannian metric on \({\rm Gr}(k,D)\) as follows:_

\[g_{[\bm{Y}]}\left(\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]},\bm{\eta}_{[\bm{Y}]}\right):=\overline{g} _{\bm{Y}}\left(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h},\overline{\bm{\eta}}_{\bm{Y }}^{\rm h}\right)={\rm tr}\left(\bm{B}^{\top}\bm{D}\right),\] (100)

_where \(\bm{B}\) and \(\bm{D}\) are matrices that are \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}=\bm{Y}_{\perp}\bm{B}\) and \(\overline{\bm{\eta}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\rm h}=\bm{Y}_{\perp}\bm{D}\), respectively._

### Invariant Measures

Let the column vectors of matrix \(\bm{Y}=\{\bm{y}_{1},\cdots,\bm{y}_{k}\}\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times k}\) be the orthonormal basis that span the subspace \(\mathrm{span}(\bm{Y})\in\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) in \(\mathbb{R}^{D}\), and the column vectors of \(\bm{Y}_{\perp}=\{\bm{y}_{k+1},\cdots,\bm{y}_{D}\}\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times D-k}\) be the orthogonal complementary space \(\mathrm{span}(\bm{Y}_{\perp})\) of \(\mathrm{span}(\bm{Y})\), respectively. Then, the following differential form can be defined.

\[(d\bm{Y}) =\bigwedge_{j=1}^{D-k}\bigwedge_{i=1}^{k}\bm{y}_{k+j}^{\top}d\bm{y }_{i}\] (101) \[=\left(\bm{y}_{k+1}^{\top}d\bm{y}_{1}\wedge\cdots\wedge\bm{y}_{k +1}^{\top}d\bm{y}_{k}\right)\wedge\cdots\wedge\left(\bm{y}_{D}^{\top}d\bm{y}_{ 1}\wedge\cdots\wedge\bm{y}_{D}^{\top}d\bm{y}_{k}\right),\] (102)

where \(\wedge\) is the wedge product and the relation satisfies \(\omega_{i}\wedge\omega_{i}=\omega_{j}\wedge\omega_{j}=0\) and \(\omega_{i}\wedge\omega_{j}=-\omega_{j}\wedge\omega_{i}\). The above equation is in \(k\left(D-k\right)\)-order differential form, which is an invariant measure on \(\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\)(Chikuse (2003)).

If we define the matrix \(\bm{X}_{\perp}\) to be \([\begin{array}{cc}\bm{X}&\bm{X}_{\perp}\end{array}]\) for any point \(\bm{X}=\{\bm{x}_{1},\cdots,\bm{x}_{k}\}\in\mathrm{St}(k,D)\), the differential form for an invariant measure on \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) is defined as follows.

\[(d\bm{X})=\bigwedge_{j=1}^{D-k}\bigwedge_{i=1}^{k}\bm{x}_{k+j}^{\top}d\bm{x}_{ i}\bigwedge_{i<j}^{k}\bm{x}_{j}^{\top}d\bm{x}_{i}=\left(d\bm{Y}\right)\left(d \bm{Q}\right),\] (103)

where \((d\bm{Q})\) is the invariant measure of \(\mathcal{O}(k)\). The integral of (103), that is, the volume of \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\), can be evaluated as follows:

\[V_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}=\int_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}\left(d\bm{X}\right).\] (104)

(104) can be computed as follows. First, the surface \(S_{D}\) of the \(D\)-dimensional unit sphere can be defined as follows:

\[S_{D}=\left.\frac{d}{dr}\right|_{r=1}V_{D}=DV_{D}=\frac{D\pi^{\frac{D}{2}}}{ \Gamma\left(\frac{D}{2}+1\right)}=\frac{2\pi^{\frac{D}{2}}}{\Gamma\left(\frac {D}{2}\right)},\] (105)

where \(V_{D}\) is the volume of a \(D\)-dimensional sphere \(\frac{\pi^{\frac{D}{2}}}{\Gamma\left(\frac{D}{2}+1\right)}r^{D}\) and \(\Gamma\left(\frac{D}{2}\right)\) is the gamma function. Then, the following equation is obtained.

\[\int_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}\left(d\bm{X}\right)=S_{D}\int_{\mathrm{St}(k-1,D-1)} \left(d\bm{X}_{1}\right),\] (106)

where \((d\bm{X}_{1})\) is the differential form of \(\mathrm{St}(k-1,D-1)\). Thus, (104) can be transformed as follows.

\[V_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}=\int_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}\left(d\bm{X}\right)=\prod_{i=1}^{ k}S_{D}=\frac{2^{k}\pi^{\frac{Dk}{2}}}{\Gamma_{k}\left(\frac{D}{2}\right)},\] (107)

where \(\Gamma_{k}\left(\frac{D}{2}\right)\) is the multidimensional gamma function. The invariant measure \((d\bm{X})\) is an un-normalized measure. A measure normalized to be a probability measure can be formulated as follows:

\[[d\bm{X}]=\frac{1}{V_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}}\left(d\bm{X}\right).\] (108)

This is a uniform distribution on \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\). As \(\mathrm{St}(k,k)=\mathcal{O}(k)\), the volume \(V_{\mathcal{O}(k)}\) of \(\mathcal{O}(k)\) can be represented using \((d\bm{Q})\) as follows.

\[V_{\mathcal{O}(k)}=V_{\mathrm{St}(k,k)}=\frac{2^{k}\pi^{\frac{k^{2}}{2}}}{ \Gamma_{k}\left(\frac{k}{2}\right)}.\] (109)

Furthermore, a measure normalized to be a probability measure can be represented by the following:

\[[d\bm{Q}]=\frac{1}{V_{\mathcal{O}(k)}}\left(d\bm{Q}\right).\] (110)From the above, the probability density function \(U_{\mathcal{O}(k)}\left(\bm{Q}\right)\) of the uniform distribution on \(\mathcal{O}(k)\) is as follows:

\[U_{\mathcal{O}(k)}\left(\bm{Q}\right)=\frac{1}{V_{\mathcal{O}(k)}}\quad\text{s.t.}\quad\bm{Q}\in\mathcal{O}(k)\,,\] (111)

\[\int_{\mathcal{O}(k)}U_{\mathcal{O}(k)}\left(\bm{Q}\right)\left(d\bm{Q}\right) =\int_{\mathcal{O}(k)}\frac{1}{V_{\mathcal{O}(k)}}\left(d\bm{Q} \right)=\int_{\mathcal{O}(k)}\left[d\bm{Q}\right]=1.\] (112)

As \(\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) is defined as a quotient manifold \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\left/\mathcal{O}(k)\right.\) as in (2), the volume \(V_{\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)}\) of \(\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) can be defined as follows.

\[V_{\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)}=\int_{\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)}\left(d\bm{Y}\right)=\frac{V_{ \mathrm{St}(k,D)}}{V_{\mathcal{O}(k)}}=\frac{V_{\mathrm{St}(k,D)}}{V_{ \mathrm{St}(k,k)}}=\frac{\pi^{\frac{k(D-k)}{2}}\Gamma_{k}\left(\frac{k}{2} \right)}{\Gamma_{k}\left(\frac{D}{2}\right)}.\] (113)

The measure normalized to be a probability measure is expressed as:

\[\left[d\bm{Y}\right]=\frac{1}{V_{\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)}}\left(d\bm{Y}\right).\] (114)

### Retraction

In general, the points except the origin \(\left(\bm{p}\left(0\right)=\bm{x}\right)\) of the tangent space \(T_{\bm{x}}\mathcal{M}\) at \(\bm{x}\) on the manifold \(\mathcal{M}\) are not elements on \(\mathcal{M}\) (\(\bm{p}\left(t\right)\in T_{\bm{x}}\mathcal{M},t\neq 0\)). Therefore, if the result of the operation on the tangent space is to be used at another point on the manifold \(\mathcal{M}\), it is necessary to map \(\bm{p}\left(t\right)\) to the manifold \(\mathcal{M}\). The map from a tangent space to a manifold is referred to as an exponential map. However, because the exponential map is computationally expensive, retraction based on numerical linear algebra is often used as an alternative (Zhu & Sato (2021)). Retraction is a method for approximating an exponential map to first order while maintaining global convergence in optimization algorithms on Riemannian manifolds. The most commonly used retractions on \(\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) are methods based on QR decomposition or singular-value decomposition (SVD) (Absil et al. (2008); Zhu & Sato (2021)). In addition, a retraction based on the Cayley transform is introduced in Zhu & Sato (2021). This retraction is closely related to the Cayley transform on \(\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) (Wen & Yin (2013); Xiaojing (2017); Zhu & Duan (2019)) and the Projected polynomial retraction (Gawlik & Leok (2018a)).

#### d.6.1 Exponential Map and Retraction

Geodesics on \(\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) can be expressed as the equivalence class \(\left[\exp_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{Gr}}\left(t\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right)\right]\), where

\[\exp_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{Gr}}\left(t\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right)=\left[ \begin{array}{cc}\bm{Y}&\bm{Y}_{\perp}\end{array}\right]\exp\left(t \mathfrak{B}\right)\bm{I}_{D\times k}.\] (115)

Here, \(\exp\) on the right-hand side is the matrix exponential, and \(\mathfrak{B}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}\bm{0}_{k}&-\bm{B}^{\top}\\ \bm{B}&\bm{0}_{D-k}\end{array}\right]\in\mathrm{skew}\left(D\right)\), where \(\bm{B}\) satisfies \(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}=\bm{Y}_{\perp}\bm{B}\). We can use a following exponential map that is mathematically equivalent to (115) (Edelman et al. (1998)):

\[\exp_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{Gr}}\left(t\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right):=\left\{ \bm{Y}\bm{V}\cos\left(\bm{\Sigma}t\right)+\bm{U}\sin\left(\bm{\Sigma}t\right) \right\}\bm{V}^{\top},\] (116)

where \(\bm{U},\bm{\Sigma},\bm{V}^{\top}=\mathrm{SVD}\left(\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y }}\right)\).

Further, we can use the Pade approximation to approximate geodesics on Grassmann manifolds as follows:

\[\bm{Y}(t)=\left[\begin{array}{cc}\bm{Y}&\bm{Y}_{\perp}\end{array}\right]r_{m} (t\mathfrak{B})\bm{I}_{D\times k}\approx\exp_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{Gr}}\left(t \overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right),\] (117)

where \(r_{m}\left(\bm{X}\right)\) is the \(m\)th-order diagonal Pade approximation to the matrix exponential \(\exp\left(\bm{X}\right)\). See the expression of \(r_{m}\left(\bm{X}\right)\) in Moler & Loan (2003). The simplest member of this class is surely the first-order Pade approximation

\[\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\left(t\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right):= \left[\begin{array}{cc}\bm{Y}&\bm{Y}_{\perp}\end{array}\right]r_{1} \left(t\mathfrak{B}\right)\bm{I}_{D\times k}\] (118) \[= \left[\begin{array}{cc}\bm{Y}&\bm{Y}_{\perp}\end{array}\right] \left(I_{n}-\frac{t}{2}\mathfrak{B}\right)^{-1}\left(\bm{I}_{D}+\frac{t}{2} \mathfrak{B}\right)\bm{I}_{D\times k},\] (119)

which is also known as the Cayley transform. From the error expression \(\exp\left(\bm{Y}\right)=r_{m}\left(\bm{Y}\right)+O\left(\|\bm{Y}\|^{2m+1}\right)\) of the Pade approximation, we have

\[\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\left(t\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right)=\exp_{\bm{Y}}^{ \mathrm{Gr}}\left(t\overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right)+O\left(t^{2m+1}\left\| \overline{\bm{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\right\|^{2m+1}\right),\] (120)

which is also given by Theorem 3 in Gawlik & Leok (2018b).

#### d.6.2 Horizontal Retraction

From Definition 3 in Zhu and Sato (2021), (119) is a horizontal retraction, and

\[R_{[\bm{Y}]}\left(t\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\right):=\left[\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\left( t\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\right)\right]\] (121)

is a retraction on \(\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) as a quotient manifold defined by (2). This is because \(\overline{R}\) satisfies the invariance condition that for all \(\bm{Y}\in\mathrm{St}(k,D)\,,\bm{Y}^{\prime}\in\mathrm{St}(k,D)\,,\bm{\bar{\xi} }_{\bm{Y}}\in T^{\mathrm{h}}_{\bm{Y}}\,\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) and \(\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}^{\prime}}\in T^{\mathrm{h}}_{\bm{Y}^{\prime}}\,\mathrm{ St}(k,D)\) such that \(\bm{Y}\sim\bm{Y}^{\prime}\) and \(\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}\) and \(\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}^{\prime}}\) are horizontal lifts of \(\bm{\xi}_{[\bm{Y}]}\in T_{[\bm{Y}]}\,\mathrm{Gr}(k,D)\) at \(\bm{Y}\) and \(\bm{Y}^{\prime}\), respectively.

In low-rank cases, we can obtain an economical version of (119) as follows (Zhu and Sato (2021)).

\[\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\left(t\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\right)=\bm{Y} +t\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}-\left(\frac{t^{2}}{2}\bm{Y}+\frac{t^{3 }}{4}\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\right)\left(\bm{I}_{k}+\frac{t^{2}} {4}\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}\top}\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h }}\right)^{-1}\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}\top}\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{ \mathrm{h}}.\] (122)

The inverse retraction \(\left(\overline{R_{[\bm{Y}]}^{-1}}\right)_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}:\mathrm{St}(k, D)\to T^{\mathrm{h}}_{\bm{Y}}\,\mathrm{St}(k,D)\) of \(\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}\left(\bm{\bar{\xi}}_{\bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}}\right)\) is the following:

\[\left(\overline{R_{[\bm{Y}]}^{-1}\left([\bm{X}]\right)}\right)_{ \bm{Y}}^{\mathrm{h}} =\overline{R}_{\bm{Y}}^{-1}\left(\bm{X}\right)\] (123) \[=2\bm{Y}_{\perp}\bm{Y}_{\perp}^{\top}\bm{X}\left(\bm{I}_{k}+\bm{ Y}^{\top}\bm{X}\right)^{-1}\] (124) \[=2\left(\bm{X}-\bm{Y}\bm{Y}^{\top}\bm{X}\right)\left(\bm{I}_{k}+ \bm{Y}^{\top}\bm{X}\right)^{-1}.\] (125)